'''''Silhouette''''' was a [[show car]] built by [[Bill Cushenberry]] in 1962. It debuted at the [[1963 Oakland Roadster Show]], and earned Cushenberry his first Master Builder Award.{{sfnp|Mauldin|1998|page=83}} In 1968, it was also one of the first sixteen [[Hot Wheels]] cars.<ref >{{Cite web |title=The Original 16 Hot Wheels Cars From 1968: The Redline Era |date=18 September 2018 |author=Anthony Altorenna |url=https://hobbylark.com/collecting/1968-hot-wheels-car-list |website=Hobby Lark.com |accessdate=20 April 2019 }}</ref>
== History == Designed in collaboration with artist Don Varner, ''Silhouette'' was Cushenberry's first full-on show car. He hand-hammered 20-gauge steel over a shortened 1956 Buick chassis, fitting a front-hinged bubble canopy (supplied by Acry Plastics).{{sfnp|Mauldin|1998|page=83–84, 87}} It was candy-painted, mixed with black, red, and gold.{{sfnp|Mauldin|1998|page=83}} The car was powered by a [[Buick]] [[Buick V8 engine#Buick "Nailhead V8" (first generation)|nailhead V8]] (later fitted with [[Stuart Hilborn|Hilborn]] [[fuel injection]]) and ran on reversed [[Cadillac]] wheels.{{sfnp|Mauldin|1998|page=83}} Like a number of other [[show rod]]s at the time, including [[The Mantaray (show rod)|''The Mantaray '']], it had a bubble canopy.<ref >{{Cite magazine |last=Rothermel |first=Rich |title=Dean Jeffries: Runnin' Flat Out Since 1951 |magazine=[[Rod & Custom]] |date=April 2000 |ref={{harvid|Rothermel|2000}} |pages=67, 71 }}</ref>
''Silhouette'' debuted at the [[1963 Oakland Roadster Show]], and earned Cushenberry his first Master Builder Award.{{sfnp|Mauldin|1998|page=83}}
Around 1968, the engine was changed to a {{convert|289|cid|cc|abbr=on}} [[Ford V8 engine|Ford]]. The car appeared in a 1968 television special, "Wonderful World of Wheels".{{sfnp|Mauldin|1998|page=87}}
Somewhat later, ''Silhouette'' was stolen and disappeared; in 1998, the car's location remained unknown.{{sfnp|Mauldin|1998|page=88}} In 2013, the bubble top and some mechanical parts had been located, but the engine and the rest of the body remained missing.<ref >{{Cite web |title=Where is the Bill Cushenbery Silhouette? |date=5 July 2013 |website=Jalopy Journal |url=https://www.jalopyjournal.com/forum/threads/where-is-the-bill-cushenbery-silhouette.814678/ }}</ref>
